            <div type="edition" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="grc" resp="#martaf">
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1"/><persName type="attested"><name>Σαβοῦκις</name>
                    <lb n="2"/><name>Καλλίμορφ<hi rend="ligature">ος</hi></name></persName>
                    <lb n="3"/><w>ἔζησεν</w> <g ref="#interpunct">·</g> <w>ἔ<hi rend="ligature">τη</hi></w> <g ref="#interpunct">·</g>
                    <lb n="4"/><g ref="#interpunct">·</g> <num value="32">λβ</num> <g ref="#interpunct">·</g> <persName type="attested"><name>Σαβούκις</name> <g ref="#interpunct">·</g>
                    <lb n="5"/><name>Ζωίλ<hi rend="ligature">ος</hi></name></persName> <g ref="#interpunct">·</g> <w>πάτ<hi rend="ligature">ρων</hi></w> <g ref="#interpunct">·</g>
                    <lb n="6"/><w>ἐποίησε</w> <g ref="#interpunct">·</g>
                </ab>
            </div>
            <div type="apparatus" resp="#martaf">
                <listApp>
                    <app><note>Text based on photographs</note></app>
                    <app loc="line 5"><note>Franz: πατρῶνι; Manganaro interpreted Πάτρων as a proper name</note></app>
                </listApp>
            </div>
            <div type="translation" xml:lang="en" resp="#martaf">
                <p>Saboukis Kallimorphos, lived for 32 years. Saboukis Zoilos, his patron (made this).</p>
            </div>
            <div type="translation" xml:lang="it" resp="#martaf">
                <p>Saboukis Kallimorphos visse 32 anni. Saboukis Zoilos, suo patrono (realizzò questo).</p>
            </div>
            <div type="commentary" resp="#martaf">
                <p>The epitaph presents the traditional structure with the name of the deceased, the indication of his age (with the verb <foreign xml:lang="grc">ζάω</foreign> in the aorist form) and a second sentence with the name of the dedicant in the nominative form and the dedication verb (<foreign xml:lang="grc">ποιέω</foreign> in the aorist form). The formulae and the palaeography are characteristic of Catania and of a 2nd-century CE dating, according to Korhonen (2004: 229; contra Manganaro 1959: 242, who dated the inscription to the 4th cent. CE). The epitaph was dedicated to a libertus Saboukis Kallimorphos by his patron Saboukis Zoilos (<foreign xml:lang="grc">πάτρων</foreign> is not part of the proper name of the dedicant, as Manganaro suggested: see J. and L. Robert, BE 1961: 268 nr. 861). The patron belonged to the <foreign xml:lang="la">gens Sabucia</foreign>, who seems to have owned several latifundia in Sicily, as numerous toponyms attest: see Manganaro 1959.</p>
            </div>
